(Viechtbauer, 2010)

cbt <- 
  read_excel("data/database_meta_anxiety.xlsx") %>% 
  clean_names()

I think in the CMA you used the “method-of-moments estimator”. According to Viechtbauer (2005), it is better to use the restricted maximum likelihood estimator. Using this only slightly changes the results, but IMO it is a more appropriate and defensible choice.

# Model for the children self-report MA
selfrep_df <- 
  cbt %>% 
  filter(outcome == "children") 

mod_selfrep <-  rma(yi = hedges_g, 
      sei = se_hedges_g, 
      data = selfrep_df, 
      method = "REML")

# Create tables that will be added to the forest plot
selfrep_table <-
  cbt %>% 
  filter(outcome == "children") %>% 
  select(Study = study, N = sample_size)

selfrep_summary <- 
  selfrep_table %>% 
  group_by(name = "Aggregated effect") %>% 
  summarise(N = sum(N))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
rate_table <-
  cbt %>%  
  filter(outcome == "clinician") %>% 
  select(Study = study, N = sample_size)

rate_summary <- 
  rate_table %>% 
  group_by(name = "Aggregated effect") %>% 
  summarise(N = sum(N))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

forest(mod_selfrep, 
       top = 3, 
       xlab = "Hedges' g", 
       slab = selfrep_table$Study,
       mlab = "Aggregated effect", 
       ilab = selfrep_table$N, 
       ilab.xpos = -1.5)

2 Funnel plots

2.1 Self-report

2.1.1 metafor

The first is a normal funnel plot, the second is a normal with trim-and-fill, the third is a contour enhanced funnel plot with trim-and-fill, centered on 0 (no effect). (Peters et al., 2008; van Assen et al., 2015)

funnel(mod_selfrep, 
       shade=c("white", "gray55"),
       legend = TRUE)

trimfill(mod_selfrep) %>% 
  funnel(., 
         shade=c("white", "gray55"),
         legend = TRUE)

trimfill(mod_selfrep) %>% 
  funnel(., 
         level=c(90, 95), 
         shade=c("white", "gray55", "gray75"),
         refline=0,
         legend = TRUE)

As there seems to be some publication or small study bias, we can try to correct for that. The model remains significant.

2.1.2 metaviz

This plot combines the zero centered contour funnel plot with the traditional funnel plot with the estimated effect (solid black vertical line), and the trim-and-fill adjusted aggregated effect size (dashed line). The TAF studies are filled, the real studies are hollow (I want to reverse that).

viz_funnel(mod_selfrep, 
           method = "RE",
           sig_contours = TRUE, 
           contours = TRUE,
           trim_and_fill = TRUE,
           text_size = 4
           ) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, alpha = .2, color = "blue", size = 2)

References

Peters, J. L., Sutton, A. J., Jones, D. R., Abrams, K. R., & Rushton, L. (2008). Contour-enhanced meta-analysis funnel plots help distinguish publication bias from other causes of asymmetry. Journal of Clinical Epidemiology, 61(10), 991–996. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclinepi.2007.11.010

van Assen, M. A. L. M., van Aert, R. C. M., & Wicherts, J. M. (2015). Meta-analysis using effect size distributions of only statistically significant studies. Psychological Methods, 20(3), 293–309. https://doi.org/10.1037/met0000025

Viechtbauer, W. (2010). Conducting Meta-Analyses in R with the metafor Package. Journal of Statistical Software, 36(3), 121108. https://doi.org/10.18637/jss.v036.i03

Viechtbauer, W. (2005). Bias and Efficiency of Meta-Analytic Variance Estimators in the Random-Effects Model. Journal of Educational and Behavioral Statistics, 30(3), 261–293. https://doi.org/10.3102/10769986030003261
